text: In each sub-figures (a)–(f) of Fig. 4, the x-coordinate pertains to the ratio of the number of the inserted objects and original data, while the y-coordinate concerns the computational time. According to the experimental results as shown in Table 9 and Fig. 4, we find that the computational time of both static (Algorithm 1) and incremental (Algorithm 3) algorithms are increasing monotonically along with the increasing of insert ratios. It is easy to get the incremental algorithm is always faster than the static algorithm when the inserting ratio increases from 10% to 100% according to Fig. 4(a)–(e). In Fig. 4(f), we find the incremental algorithm is mush faster than the static algorithm when the inserting ratio is less than 85%, but slower than the static algorithm when the inserting ratio is more than 85%.
